SIMPLE: swap
RECORDS: 4

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Swap
<hw>Swap</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p.
p.</pos> <conjf>Swapped</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Swapping</conjf>.]</vmorph> <ety>[OE. <ets>swappen</ets> to
strike; cf. E. to <ets>strike</ets> a bargain; perh. akin to E.
<ets>sweep</ets>. Cf. <er>Swap</er> a blow, <er>Swap</er>, <pos>v.
i.</pos>]</ety> <altsp>[Written also <asp>swop</asp>.]</altsp>
<sn>1.</sn> <def>To strike; -- with <xex>off</xex>.</def> <mark>[Obs. or
Prov. Eng.]</mark> ⟦ldquo⟧<xex>Swap</xex> off his head!⟦rdquo⟧
<rj><au>Chaucer.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To exchange (usually two things of the same kind);
to swap.</def> <mark>[Colloq.]</mark> <rj><au>Miss
Edgeworth.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Swap</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Swap
<hw>Swap</hw>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <ety>[Cf. <er>Swap</er>, <pos>v.
t.</pos>]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To fall or descend; to rush hastily or
violently.</def> <rj><au>C. Richardson (Dict.).</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>All suddenly she <qex>swapt</qex> adown to ground.</q>
<rj><qau>Chaucer.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To beat the air, or ply the wings, with a sweeping
motion or noise; to flap.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Swap</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Swap
<hw>Swap</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Cf. G. <ets>schwapp</ets>, n., a
slap, swap, <ets>schwapp</ets>, <ets>schwapps</ets>, interj., slap!
smack! and E. <ets>swap</ets>, v.t.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>A blow; a
stroke.</def> <mark>[Obs. or Prov. Eng.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>An exchange; a barter.</def> <mark>[Colloq.]</mark>
<rj><au>Sir W. Scott.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Swap</ent>⟦br⟧

